{"description":"In legacy.go, all 15+ DoctorCheck structs use raw string literals ('ok', 'warning') for the Status field instead of StatusOK, StatusWarning, StatusError constants from types.go. If these constants are ever changed, legacy.go checks will produce incorrect status values.

Also, types.go defines Status as a raw string with no type safety. Using a typed string (type Status string) would provide compile-time checking.

Suggested fix: Replace all string literals with constants. Consider adding a typed Status."}

{"description":"In git.go line ~687, when provider.GetOpenIssues(ctx) fails, FindOrphanedIssues returns ([]OrphanIssue{}, nil) — no error. This silently hides database connectivity failures, authentication issues, or other real errors. The caller CheckOrphanedIssues would report 'no orphans' when the check actually could not run.

Also, CheckGitWorkingTree and CheckGitUpstream (lines ~282-293, 383-431) run multiple exec.Command('git', ...) calls without a context timeout. If the git process hangs, the doctor check blocks indefinitely.

Suggested fix: Return the error from GetOpenIssues. Use exec.CommandContext with a timeout for git commands."}

